w did they tell us about God’s presence in the world? What epistemological and ontological purpose did these ‘others’ serve? The Scholastic Project offers an account of this intellectual work done by categories of difference in medieval theology. In so doing, it shows just how constitutive the woman, the heretic and the Jew were for the production of orthodoxy in the Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aScholasticism. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMedieval Theology.  aScholasticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066284940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781942401087zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781942401087423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781942401087/original  a978-3-11-066284-9  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK